			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/12/opinion/nyto-stress/nyto-stress-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/12/opinion/nyto-stress/nyto-stress-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/12/opinion/nyto-stress/nyto-stress-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002997446" width="592" height="592" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="592"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Dorothea Lange/U.S. Farm Security Administration</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/why-you-are-so-stressed-about-stress/" data-title="Why You Are So Stressed About Stress" data-description="A new NPR study shows that Americans are very stressed out. Is this any different from how it has always been?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">NPR conducted a <a href="//media.npr.org/documents/2014/july/npr_rwfj_harvard_stress_poll.pdf">study</a> about how stressed out we are as a country, and the <a href="//www.npr.org/blogs/health/2014/07/07/327322187/stressed-out-americans-tell-us-about-stress-in-their-lives">results</a>, released last week, show that one in four Americans reported feeling stressed in the last month and one in two has experienced a major stressful event in the last year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/quarter-americans-are-stressed-out-and-s-probably-massive-underestimate-180951983/?utm_source=twitter.com&amp;utm_medium=socialmedia&amp;utm_campaign=07112014&amp;utm_content=smartnewsamericansstressed1">Smithsonian Magazine</a>, recommending the study, reports that this likely underestimates the actual stress load on Americans: âThe survey only measures stress that people are conscious of, NPR explains, but research shows that people can suffer unaware from other forms of stress.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In short, according to Smithsonian, âstress is becoming the national psyche.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So we are barraged with new studies and ideas about stress and how it may be harming us â but many of them are contradictory.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Stress can hurt your health, but <a href="//www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/06/study-stressing-about-stress-is-bad-for-you/277254/">stressing too much about stress</a> is even worse for your health. Stress <a href="//www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/07/study-coping-poorly-with-stress-means-worse-sleep/374173/">can make you sleep badly</a> or it can <a href="//www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/12/why-some-people-respond-to-stress-by-falling-asleep/282422/">make you fall asleep</a>. People are most stressed out <a href="//www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2013/02/05/craig-wilson-wednesday-stress/1870077/">on Wednesday</a> at 3:30 p.m. And BuzzFeed made a cute video asking <a href="//www.buzzfeed.com/mitchellmoffit/can-stress-actually-kill-you-6h4x">whether stress can actually kill you</a>. (âThose under significant stress can have more clogged arteriesâ and that âcan ultimately lead to heart attack.â)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nevertheless, longstanding medical studies do show that <a href="//www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-living/stress-management/in-depth/stress/art-20046037">chronic stress</a> can lead to anxiety, depression, digestive problems, trouble sleeping, heart disease, weight gain and memory or concentration impairment. Alexandra Drane, a health care consultant, <a href="//www.npr.org/blogs/health/2014/07/08/327256681/stress-causes-health-problems-which-then-cause-more-stress">told NPR</a> that those experiencing âtoxic stressâ were â2.6 times as likely to have diabetes, 2.9 times as likely to have back pain. They were 5 times as likely to be having mental health issues.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Our economy is contributing to the strain, as elevated stress levels often correlate with downturns. In the United States, the Great Recession <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2009/04/09/health/09stress.html?pagewanted=all">brought a spike in stress and anxiety</a>. The <a href="//www.gallup.com/poll/124904/americans-less-happy-stressed-2009.aspx">Gallup-Healthways</a> <a href="//www.healthways.com/solution/default.aspx?id=1125">Well-Being Index</a> polls more than a thousand people each day and in 2008, the studyâs <a href="//usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/health/2009-03-11-stress-poll_N.htm">first year</a>, showed the definitive effects of economic hardship on stress and mental well-being.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Health concerns also weigh heavily on people. The NPR study found that those in poor health are more than twice as likely as the public as a whole to report a great deal of stress in the past month (60 percent). Eight in 10 of those in poor health reported that their own health problems contributed to their stress, while more than half (58 percent) attributed higher stress levels to the health problems of a family member. Finally, the most commonly reported effect of stressâs impact on health was poor emotional well-being.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So are we more stressed out than ever before?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Probably not. David Linden, a professor of neuroscience at Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine, said of the NPR study: âA lot of people imagine that our modern lifestyle â with constantly chirping cellphones and email and all these demands â has led to more stress. The truth is, it really doesn&#8217;t seem to be that way.â In fact, the causes of stress for Americans are âage-old troubles: illness, disease and the death of a loved one.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last year, Scott Stossel published a book called â<a href="//www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/01/surviving_anxiety/355741/">My Age of Anxiety</a>,â part memoir and part historical study, that tells the story of the crippling anxiety he has suffered since his early childhood. The book also narrates the ways in which treating anxiety have mushroomed as it has become more prevalent and addresses trends in psychotherapy, pharmaceuticals and <a href="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/30/the-mindfulness-backlash/">mindfulness</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.psyweb.com/articles/anxiety/difference-between-stress-and-anxiety">Stress and anxiety are not the exactly the same</a>: Anxiety is a diagnosable and potentially debilitating condition that is defined by having no identifiable source, whereas stress is a natural response to daily pressures or is related to a particular event. Still, descriptions of each are strikingly similar. And both, seemingly, are intrinsically related to life&#8217;s inevitable hardships.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/atlarge/2014/01/27/140127crat_atlarge_menand?currentPage=all">Louis Menand, writing about the book in The New Yorker</a>, observes that Mr. Stossel was as interested in the metaphysics of anxiety as in his own medical condition. âTo grapple with and understand anxiety,â Mr. Stossel writes, âis, in some sense, to grapple with and understand the human condition.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anxiety, Mr. Menand adds, can be understood in a variety of ways. It âcan mean that human beings are creatures who care about the future, and so hoping for good outcomes and worrying about bad ones comes with membership in the species. This is, roughly, the existentialist view.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It âcan also mean that our mental life is characterized by psychic conflict, and anxiety is the symptom of that conflict. This is, roughly, the psychoanalytic view.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In evolutionary psychology, anxiety is linked to the âfight-or-flightâ reflex, and in sociology, âanxiety is interpreted as a reaction to the stress and uncertainty of modern life.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For Mr. Menand, these ideas of anxiety, which âare not even compatible with one another,â Â share a bottom line: They indicate how fundamental it is to the experience of being human.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thankfully, there is a good side to stress. The NPR study notes that, in its primordial form, stress is meant to protect us from harm â that fight-or-flight jolt of cortisol â and for many, some stress can be galvanizing: 67 percent of those in the NPR study who reported having a great deal of stress in the past month believe that, at some point, stress has had a positive effect on some aspect of their life. About 4 in 10 say it has had a positive effect specifically on their work life.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Stress can drag us down or help us find ways to bootstrap our way up. If we canât avoid stress, at least we can choose how to respond to it.</p>
	</div>
		<footer class="entry-footer">
